\begin_layout Standard
Recurring theme 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}\cong\mathbb{CP}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is the Bloch sphere, consisting of linear combinations of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle =\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle =\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\alpha\left|\uparrow\right\rangle +\beta\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, so that is a total of four real numbers.
 Next 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \psi|\psi\right\rangle =1$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{*}\alpha+\beta^{*}\beta=1$
\end_inset

 leaves three real numbers.
 Phase ambiguity implies only two real numbers to get a point on the Bloch
 sphere.
 The third number, the phase, is physically real, in that it shows up in
 Bohm-Aharonov, and cannot be swept away; it also implies that it must be
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)$
\end_inset

 of electromagnetism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal here is to interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as a pure state, and specifically, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on a single fiber of some fiber bundle.
 That is, it is just marking a spin direction for one point in spacetime.
 Given a spacetime point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the fiber above 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(x\right)=\left\langle x|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 which has a real magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x\right)=\left\Vert \psi\left(x\right)\right\Vert ^{2}=\left|\psi^{*}\left(x\right)\psi\left(x\right)\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 here is ambiguous.
 There are several possible interpretations.
 The classical interpretation is to associate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as a single point on the Bloch sphere.
 (I think this is the mental model most physicists use).
 Another interpretation is to associate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with Killing fields on the Bloch sphere.
 We'll be using the second interpretation; this is required to overcome
 technical problems relating to Clebsh–Gordan coeficients for the two-particle
 state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this time, no physical assumptions about mixed states are being made;
 in particular, the density matrix is NOT assumed! This is because I want
 to leave open the door to a more general concept of mixed states as arbitrary
 probability distributions on the surface of the Bloch sphere, rather than
 as points in it's interior, as standard QM density matrix formalism requires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per Wikipedia, a single point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be paramterized by Hopf coordinates: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=e^{i\varphi}\cos\eta\quad\mbox{and \ensuremath{\quad\beta=e^{i\varphi}e^{i\xi}}\ensuremath{\sin\eta}}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\eta\le\pi/2$
\end_inset

: attention, this is NOT the usual sphere coord, its off by a factor of
 two! So 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=0$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The longitude is 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\xi\le2\pi$
\end_inset

.
 The phase is 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\varphi}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-sphere has three Killing vector fields.
 So, basicaly, treat 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 as a symmetric space.
 The Killing field algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}\cong\mathfrak{su}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 splits into
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m}\oplus\mathfrak{h}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}\cong TS^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}\cong\mathfrak{u}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 is the stabilizer subalgebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I assume that this is equivalent to the Hopf fibration, but this needs to
 be double-checked, with explicit expressions given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Per the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hairy ball theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, vector fields on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be combed, which is why the stabilizer 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 is not vacant.
 Picking a single point on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to picking a Killing field that is vanishing at that point.
 The other two are not, they are tangent to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}S^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

