\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The biggest problem with using Killing fields to represent a point is that
 there will also be a second spot somewhere on the sphere where a given
 Killing field must vanish.
 This problem can be avoided by noting that a given fixed Killing field
 is just one representative out of an infinite set of such fields.
 Infinite set because, at each point on the spehre, we are free to choose
 any coordinate frame we like; the Killing fields can be any wild, crazy
 combing of hair, as long as we recognize thier algebra is the algebra of
 the isometries, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{su}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 correspond to the coset of all Killing fields that vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A pure state is meant to be represented by a single point on the Bloch sphere.
