\begin_layout Subsection
The two-spin system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal here is to represent an entangled state of two qubits.
 Naively, this is an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{4}$
\end_inset

, which we will decompose into spinors, and apply normalization constraints.
 This follows the usual algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's the tricky part: this is not a fiber over a single spacetime; it
 has two spatial coordinates, one for each spinor.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the spacetime manifold, the two-spin system is a fiber over the base
 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times M$
\end_inset

.
 It has two spatial positions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the general two-particle state will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\psi_{A}\right\rangle \otimes\left|\psi_{B}\right\rangle =\left(\alpha_{A}\left|\uparrow_{A}\right\rangle +\beta_{A}\left|\downarrow_{A}\right\rangle \right)\otimes\left(\alpha_{B}\left|\uparrow_{B}\right\rangle +\beta_{B}\left|\downarrow_{B}\right\rangle \right)
\]

\end_inset

Note the tensor product makes it bilinear.
 Expanding this gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\psi_{A}\right\rangle \otimes\left|\psi_{B}\right\rangle =\alpha_{A}\alpha_{B}\left|\uparrow_{A}\uparrow_{B}\right\rangle +\alpha_{A}\beta_{B}\left|\uparrow_{A}\downarrow_{B}\right\rangle +\beta_{A}\alpha_{B}\left|\downarrow_{A}\uparrow_{B}\right\rangle +\beta_{A}\beta_{B}\left|\downarrow_{A}\downarrow_{B}\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary issue with the above expression is that a two-particle state
 cannot be determined by a pair of points on the Bloch sphere.
 For example, Bell states are the maximally entangled states.
 These are, in conventional notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\Phi^{+}\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)\\
\left|\Phi^{-}\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle -\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle \right)\\
\left|\Psi^{+}\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle \right)\\
\left|\Psi^{-}\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle -\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle \right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and there is no choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 that can express the above just a single pair of spin-1/2 states.
 So for example, to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Phi^{+}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{A}=\alpha_{B}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{A}=-\beta_{B}=i$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\psi\,1\,i\right\rangle  & =\left(\left|\uparrow_{A}\right\rangle +i\left|\downarrow_{A}\right\rangle \right)\otimes\left(\left|\uparrow_{B}\right\rangle -i\left|\downarrow_{B}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & =\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle -i\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle +i\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and also 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\psi\,1\,-i\right\rangle  & =\left(\left|\uparrow_{A}\right\rangle -i\left|\downarrow_{A}\right\rangle \right)\otimes\left(\left|\uparrow_{B}\right\rangle +i\left|\downarrow_{B}\right\rangle \right)\\
 & =\left|\uparrow\uparrow\right\rangle +i\left|\uparrow\downarrow\right\rangle -i\left|\downarrow\uparrow\right\rangle +\left|\downarrow\downarrow\right\rangle 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

in order to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|\Phi^{+}\right\rangle =\left|\psi\,1\,i\right\rangle +\left|\psi\,1\,-i\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

up to normalization.
 Thus, at least two pairs of points on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 are needed! One pair is not enough! This is the root cause of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wave function collapse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; a measurement of a Bell state discards one of these two possibilities.
\end_layout

