Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\omega=\Omega=i\sigma_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
-1 & 0
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

This defines a symplectic bilinear form on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle u,v\right\rangle =-\left\langle v,u\right\rangle =u_{1}v_{2}-u_{2}v_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
u_{1} & u_{2}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
-1 & 0
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}
\end{array}\right)=u^{T}\epsilon v
\]

\end_inset

This is invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 since for 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 one gets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle Su,Sv\right\rangle =\left\langle u,v\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 And so 
\begin_inset Formula $SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)\cong Sp\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Sp\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)=\left\{ S\in GL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)|S^{T}\epsilon S=\epsilon\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

Some useful identities: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon^{-1}=\epsilon^{T}=\epsilon^{\dagger}=-\epsilon
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon S\epsilon^{-1}=\epsilon\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
c & d
\end{array}\right)\epsilon^{-1}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
d & -c\\
-b & a
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Holds as a matrix identity, for any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{cc}
d & -c\\
-b & a
\end{array}\right)=\left(S^{-1}\right)^{T}
\]

\end_inset

So, more conventionally, for 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in SL\left(2,\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

 one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon S^{T}\epsilon^{-1}=S^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

Note how this resembles the defintion 
\begin_inset Formula $gA^{T}g^{-1}=A^{-1}$
\end_inset

