\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Two-component Majorana
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rephrasing Ase section 3 in my notation.
 So: 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{L}\left(x\right)\mapsto\psi_{L}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=\left(S^{\dagger}\right)^{-1}\psi_{L}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x\right)\mapsto\psi_{L}^{\prime*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=\left(S^{T}\right)^{-1}\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is Aste eqn 61.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(S^{T}\right)^{-1}=\epsilon^{-1}S\epsilon$
\end_inset

 therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x\right)\mapsto m\epsilon\psi_{L}^{\prime*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=Sm\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

transforms as if it is right-handed.
 The right-handed variant is 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}\left(x\right)\mapsto\psi_{R}^{\prime}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=S\psi_{R}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{R}^{*}\left(x\right)\mapsto\psi_{R}^{\prime*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=S^{*}\psi_{R}^{*}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon S^{*}=\left(S^{\dagger}\right)^{-1}\epsilon$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\epsilon\psi_{R}\left(x\right)\mapsto m\epsilon\psi_{R}^{\prime*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=\left(S^{\dagger}\right)^{-1}m\epsilon\psi_{R}^{*}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Combine the left-handed variant with the earlier result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\prime\mu}}\psi_{L}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=S\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{L}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Adding these together, one gets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\prime\mu}}\psi_{L}\left(x^{\prime}\right)\pm m\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=S\left(i\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{L}\left(x\right)\pm m\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Note that the RHS transforms like a right-handed spinor.
 Likewise,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\sigma^{\mu}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\prime\mu}}\psi_{R}\left(x^{\prime}\right)\pm m\epsilon\psi_{R}^{*}\left(x^{\prime}\right)=\left(S^{-1}\right)^{\dagger}\left(i\sigma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi_{R}\left(x\right)\pm m\epsilon\psi_{R}^{*}\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

is Lorentz covariant.
 Because the RHS's transform like Majorana, we are free to apply the operator
 on them again.
 Should get the Klein–Gordon.
 Let's do that for giggles.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 stand for charge conjugation.
 Oh, allow mass to be a complex number, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 does not commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 And label the two 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 signs (which isn't needed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is complex, but whatever...)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(i\sigma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\pm_{R}m\epsilon K\right)\left(i\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\pm_{L}m\epsilon K\right)\psi_{L}=\left(-\partial\overline{\partial}-\pm_{L}\pm_{R}\left|m\right|^{2}+im\left(\mp_{R}\epsilon K\overline{\partial}\pm_{L}\partial\epsilon K\right)\right)\psi_{L}
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon^{2}=-1$
\end_inset

 was used, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Km=m^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial\overline{\partial}=\partial_{t}^{2}-\vec{\nabla}\cdot\vec{\nabla}=\square
\]

\end_inset

To get the conventional Klein-Gordon equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\square+m^{2}\right)\psi=0$
\end_inset

 we must take 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm_{L}=\pm_{R}=\pm$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(i\sigma_{\mu}\partial^{\mu}\pm m\epsilon K\right)\left(i\overline{\sigma}_{\mu}\partial^{\mu}\pm m\epsilon K\right)\psi_{L}=\left(-\left(\square+m^{2}\right)\pm im\left(\partial\epsilon K-\epsilon K\overline{\partial}\right)\right)\psi_{L}
\]

\end_inset

But 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial=\sigma_{\mu}\partial^{\mu}=\partial_{t}-\vec{\sigma}\cdot\vec{\nabla}$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial\epsilon K-\epsilon K\overline{\partial}=-\left(\vec{\sigma}\epsilon+\epsilon\vec{\sigma}^{*}\right)\cdot\vec{\nabla}K
\]

\end_inset

while from before, we had 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon\sigma^{k}\epsilon^{-1}=-\sigma^{Tk}
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\vec{\sigma}=-\vec{\sigma}^{T}\epsilon=-K\vec{\sigma}^{\dagger}\epsilon=-K\vec{\sigma}\epsilon=-\vec{\sigma}^{*}\epsilon$
\end_inset

 so the skew term vanishes.
 Hooray!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reasonable shorthand for this seems to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{R}=i\sigma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\pm m\epsilon K
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{L}=i\overline{\sigma}^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\pm m\epsilon K
\]

\end_inset

so that Majorana is 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{L}\psi_{L}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{R}\psi_{R}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Four-component Majorana
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Should be able to re-arrange the above into a four-component Majorana.
 Start by writing
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(D_{L}\oplus D_{R}\right)\left(\psi_{L}\oplus\psi_{R}\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

which is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{L}\oplus D_{R}=i\left[\begin{array}{cc}
I & 0\\
0 & I
\end{array}\right]\partial_{t}+i\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\sigma^{i} & 0\\
0 & \sigma^{i}
\end{array}\right]\nabla_{i}\pm m\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\epsilon K & 0\\
0 & \epsilon K
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Multiply by (this is minus the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 in the chiral rep of Itzykson & Zuber)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & I\\
I & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

to get the gamma matrices in the chiral rep.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(D_{L}\oplus D_{R}\right)=i\beta\partial_{t}+i\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & \sigma^{i}\\
-\sigma^{i} & 0
\end{array}\right]\nabla_{i}\pm m\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & \epsilon K\\
\epsilon K & 0
\end{array}\right]=i\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\pm m\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & \epsilon K\\
\epsilon K & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=i\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{L}\\
\psi_{R}
\end{array}\right)\pm m\left(\begin{array}{c}
\epsilon\psi_{R}^{*}\\
\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Then writing (this is minus the chiral rep 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{5}$
\end_inset

 of Itzykson & Zuber)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-i\sigma^{2} & 0\\
0 & i\sigma^{2}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-\epsilon & 0\\
0 & \epsilon
\end{array}\right]\qquad\gamma^{5}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & 0\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the charge-conjugate spinor as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{c}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\psi_{L}^{c}\\
\psi_{R}^{c}
\end{array}\right)=C\overline{\psi}^{T}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
0 & -\epsilon\\
\epsilon & 0
\end{array}\right]\psi^{*}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\epsilon\psi_{R}^{*}\\
\epsilon\psi_{L}^{*}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

the final four-component eqn is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=i\gamma^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\psi\pm m\gamma^{5}\psi_{c}
\]

\end_inset

Looks weird.
 Does it work? Not really...
\end_layout

